# Test Failure Triage Protocol

## Test Failure Ownership Triage

For each failing test, determine ownership:

1. Run the same test on the base branch (uses detached HEAD instead of branch checkout):
   ```bash
   CURRENT=$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD) && git stash && git fetch origin {{ trunk_branch }} && git switch --detach origin/{{ trunk_branch }} && {{ ci_command }} 2>&1; git switch "$CURRENT" && git stash pop
   ```
   (Or use `git diff origin/{{ trunk_branch }}...HEAD` to check if the failing test file was modified on this branch)

2. **Pre-existing failure** (fails on base branch too): Note it, continue. Not your problem.
3. **In-branch failure** (passes on base, fails on HEAD): This IS your problem. Must fix.

**After triage:** If in-branch failures remain, enter the fix loop.
If all failures were pre-existing, continue to next step.

**If all pass:** Continue silently — note the counts briefly.

## Fix Loop

If the code review verdict is `ITERATE`, or if in-branch test failures remain:

1. Apply fixes for ALL actionable findings (CRITICAL first, then WARN)
2. Re-run `{{ ci_command }}`
3. If new failures: re-enter triage
4. Max fix rounds: {{ max_iterations }} (configurable via `workflow.max_iterations`)
5. After max rounds with remaining failures: document in PR body and proceed

## Error Recovery Matrix

| Error Type | Signal | Recovery |
|------------|--------|----------|
| CI lint failure | linter errors | `ruff check --fix` or equivalent, commit, re-run |
| CI type check | type checker errors | fix annotations, re-run |
| Git conflict | merge conflict markers | report to user, do not attempt resolution |
| Import error | ModuleNotFoundError | check missing dep, add to requirements |
| Permission error | PermissionError | report to user |
